Asynchronous FIFO in Verilog
Overview

This project implements an Asynchronous FIFO (First-In First-Out) in Verilog HDL.
It is used to safely transfer data between two different clock domains, where the write side and read side operate on independent clocks.

The design uses:

Separate write and read clocks
FIFO memory for temporary data storage
Binary pointers for addressing
Gray code pointers for safe clock-domain crossing
Two-flop synchronizers for pointer synchronization
Full and Empty flag generation

This project is useful for understanding a very important digital design concept: Clock Domain Crossing (CDC).

Project Structure
03_Asynchronous FIFO/
│── async_fifo.v       # RTL design of asynchronous FIFO
│── tb_async_fifo.v    # Testbench for simulation
│── schematic.png      # RTL / schematic view
│── waveform.png       # Simulation waveform
What is an Asynchronous FIFO?

A FIFO stores data in the order it is written.

FIFO = First In First Out
The first data written is the first data read
Used when producer and consumer work at different clock frequencies

Unlike a synchronous FIFO, an asynchronous FIFO has:

wr_clk → write clock
rd_clk → read clock

Since these two clocks are independent, special care is needed to avoid metastability and incorrect pointer transfer. That is why Gray code and pointer synchronization are used.

Module Description
Top Module
module async_fifo
Parameters
parameter width = 8,
parameter depth = 8
width → number of bits in each FIFO data word
depth → number of storage locations in the FIFO

For this project:

FIFO data width = 8 bits
FIFO depth = 8 entries
Port Description
Inputs
input rd_clk,
input wr_clk,
input rd_en,
input wr_en,
input rst,
input [width-1:0] data_in
wr_clk : clock used for writing data into FIFO
rd_clk : clock used for reading data from FIFO
wr_en : write enable
rd_en : read enable
rst : reset signal
data_in: input data to be written
Outputs
output reg [width-1:0] data_out,
output full,
output empty
data_out : data read from FIFO
full : indicates FIFO is full
empty : indicates FIFO is empty
Internal Design
FIFO Memory

The data is stored in an internal memory array:

reg [width-1:0] FIFO [depth-1:0];

For depth = 8, this creates 8 storage locations, each of 8 bits.

Address Width
localparam addr_width = $clog2(depth);

For depth = 8:

addr_width = 3

So 3 bits are needed to address 8 FIFO locations.

Pointer Logic

The FIFO uses:

Write pointer → wb_ptr
Read pointer → rb_ptr
reg [addr_width:0] wb_ptr, rb_ptr;

These pointers are one bit wider than the address width.
The extra bit helps distinguish between full and empty conditions after pointer wrap-around.

Write Operation

The write logic is:

always @(posedge wr_clk or posedge rst) begin
    if (rst)
        wb_ptr <= 0;
    else if (wr_en && !full) begin
        FIFO[wb_ptr[addr_width-1:0]] <= data_in;
        wb_ptr <= wb_ptr + 1;
    end
end
Working
On reset, write pointer becomes 0
If wr_en = 1 and FIFO is not full:
data_in is written into FIFO memory
write pointer increments
Important statement
FIFO[wb_ptr[addr_width-1:0]] <= data_in;

Only the lower address bits of the pointer are used to select the FIFO location.

Read Operation

The read logic is:

always @(posedge rd_clk or posedge rst) begin
    if (rst) begin
        rb_ptr <= 0;
        data_out <= 0;
    end
    else if (rd_en && !empty) begin
        data_out <= FIFO[rb_ptr[addr_width-1:0]];
        rb_ptr <= rb_ptr + 1;
    end
end
Working
On reset, read pointer and output are cleared
If rd_en = 1 and FIFO is not empty:
data is read from FIFO
read pointer increments
Important statement
data_out <= FIFO[rb_ptr[addr_width-1:0]];

The data stored at the current read pointer location is sent to data_out.

Gray Code Conversion

In an asynchronous FIFO, pointers must be safely transferred between different clock domains.
Directly sending binary pointers is risky because multiple bits may change at the same time.

To avoid this, the design converts binary pointers to Gray code:

assign wg_ptr = (wb_ptr >> 1) ^ wb_ptr;
assign rg_ptr = (rb_ptr >> 1) ^ rb_ptr;
Why Gray code?

Gray code changes only one bit at a time, which makes pointer synchronization across clock domains much safer.

wg_ptr → Gray-coded write pointer
rg_ptr → Gray-coded read pointer
Pointer Synchronization

Since write and read clocks are different:

the read side must know the write pointer to detect empty
the write side must know the read pointer to detect full

This is done using two-flop synchronizers.

Synchronizing Write Pointer into Read Clock Domain
always @(posedge rd_clk or posedge rst) begin
    if (rst) begin
        wg_ptr_sync1 <= 0;
        wg_ptr_sync2 <= 0;
    end
    else begin
        wg_ptr_sync1 <= wg_ptr;
        wg_ptr_sync2 <= wg_ptr_sync1;
    end
end

This safely transfers the write Gray pointer into the read clock domain.

Synchronizing Read Pointer into Write Clock Domain
always @(posedge wr_clk or posedge rst) begin
    if (rst) begin
        rg_ptr_sync1 <= 0;
        rg_ptr_sync2 <= 0;
    end
    else begin
        rg_ptr_sync1 <= rg_ptr;
        rg_ptr_sync2 <= rg_ptr_sync1;
    end
end

This safely transfers the read Gray pointer into the write clock domain.

Empty Flag Logic
assign empty = (rg_ptr == wg_ptr_sync2);
Meaning

FIFO is empty when:

current read pointer
equals the synchronized write pointer

That means all written data has already been read.

Full Flag Logic
assign wb_ptr_next = wb_ptr + 1;
assign wg_ptr_next = (wb_ptr_next >> 1) ^ wb_ptr_next;
assign full = (wg_ptr_next == {~rg_ptr_sync2[addr_width:addr_width-1], rg_ptr_sync2[addr_width-2:0]});
Meaning

FIFO becomes full when the next write pointer reaches the read pointer in the full-condition Gray code pattern.

This logic prevents overflow by blocking writes when the FIFO is full.

Full and Empty Protection
Write protection
else if (wr_en && !full)

A write happens only when FIFO is not full.

Read protection
else if (rd_en && !empty)

A read happens only when FIFO is not empty.

These two conditions prevent:

overflow during write
underflow during read
Testbench Description

The file tb_async_fifo.v verifies the FIFO by:

generating separate write and read clocks
applying reset
writing multiple values into the FIFO
reading values back from the FIFO
checking full, empty, and data_out
Clock Generation in Testbench
Write clock
initial wr_clk = 0;
always #5 wr_clk = ~wr_clk;
Write clock period = 10 time units
Read clock
initial rd_clk = 0;
always #12 rd_clk = ~rd_clk;
Read clock period = 24 time units

This confirms that the FIFO is working between two independent clocks.

Testbench Operation
Reset phase

Initially:

rst = 1
write and read disabled
FIFO starts in reset state

After some delay, reset is released and FIFO begins operation.

Write phase

The testbench writes a sequence of values into the FIFO using wr_clk.

Example logic:

if (!full) begin
    wr_en <= 1;
    data_in <= i;
end

Data is written until FIFO becomes full.

Read phase

The testbench then reads values using rd_clk.

Example logic:

if (!empty) begin
    rd_en <= 1;
end

Data is read in the same order in which it was written.

Expected Behavior
After reset
empty = 1
full = 0
During writes
Data is stored into FIFO
Write pointer increments
full becomes 1 when FIFO capacity is reached
During reads
Data appears on data_out
Read pointer increments
empty becomes 1 after all stored data is read
Key Concepts Demonstrated

This project demonstrates the following digital design concepts:

Asynchronous FIFO architecture
Clock Domain Crossing (CDC)
Binary and Gray code pointer handling
Two-stage synchronizers
Full and Empty flag generation
Safe transfer of data between different clock domains
Applications

Asynchronous FIFOs are commonly used in:

UART / SPI / serial interfaces
Processor to peripheral communication
Data buffering between modules with different clocks
FPGA and ASIC CDC paths
Streaming and packet-based systems
